# React Native Engineering Rules

## Simplicity and component boundaries
- Keep UI simple, predictable, and readable in one pass.
- One component solves one problem; split components as soon as they grow.
- Separate presentation, business logic, and data access.
- Keep props minimal, explicit, and predictable; avoid magic numbers.
- In the page-system, each major section item must be implemented as its own block type rather than a large monolithic JSX file.
- Any new block type must be registered in `@/page-system/blocks/index.jsx` before usage.
- Prefer nested block composition via `innerBlocks` for section structures; avoid handling full-page section trees inside one component file.

## Layout and styling
- Never use margin for spacing.
- Use `gap` for spacing between siblings and `padding` for internal spacing.
- Parent components own layout; children must not control outer spacing.
- Use one spacing scale across the app.
- Use intent-based style names and keep visual hierarchy obvious.

## Safe area ownership
- Root-level safe area handling is centralized in `@/components/RootContainer/RootContainer.jsx`.
- Do not add `useSafeAreaInsets`/SafeArea padding again in normal screens, navigators, tab bars, or shared layout wrappers when root already defines it.
- Modal surfaces are treated differently from screens; modals must apply safe area insets locally when needed.

## Interaction, gestures, and animation
- Use `Pressable` for taps; do not use legacy touchables.
- Use `react-native-gesture-handler` for gestures (drag/swipe/pan/pinch).
- Use `react-native-reanimated` for animations.
- Any per-frame or per-touch logic must run on the UI thread, not JS.

## Lists and render performance
- Use `FlatList` or `FlashList` for non-trivial or dynamic lists.
- Do not use `ScrollView` for long lists and do not nest scroll views.
- Avoid heavy logic during render and avoid inline functions in list items.
- Memoize expensive calculations and use stable keys (never array index).

## State and data flow
- Use Zustand only for client UI/session state (not server data).
- Use MMKV only for small persistent values (tokens, preferences, startup flags).
- Use TanStack Query for all server state with consistent query keys.
- Keep API flow: Component -> Hook -> Query/Mutation -> Axios.

## API and helpers
- Use exactly one Axios client instance with centralized interceptors.
- Never call Axios directly inside components.
- Keep helper files pure and single-responsibility.
- Shared hooks start with `use`, have one responsibility, and avoid unnecessary side effects.

## Imports and path alias
- Use the `@/` alias for imports from `src/` (e.g. `@/constants/colors`, `@/config/tabs`, `@/redux/store`, `@/page-system/pages`, `@/screens/PageScreen`, `@/components/...`, `@/navigation/...`, `@/hooks/...`).
- Do not use long relative paths for cross-directory imports (e.g. avoid `../../constants/colors`); use `@/constants/colors` instead.
- Same-folder or same-package imports may use `./` (e.g. `./styles`, `./data`, `./blocks`).

## Platform and dependency constraints
- Keep behavior predictable across web and mobile without layout hacks.
- Share business logic across platforms.
- Do not introduce deprecated, unmaintained, JS-thread-heavy, or web-first libraries for critical native paths.
- Prefer the simplest complete solution; avoid over-engineering.

## Responsiveness practices (react-native-size-matters)
- Use `react-native-size-matters` scaling helpers for responsive dimensions.
- Import only what is needed from `s`, `vs`, `ms`, and `mvs`.
- Use `s()`/`ms()` for horizontal values and `vs()`/`mvs()` for vertical values.
- For square elements (icons, avatars, badges), use one scale function for both width and height (for example `ms(x)` for both).
- Do not mix `s()` for width and `vs()` for height on the same square element.
- Do not copy Figma pixel values 1:1; use practical base values and treat size-matters outputs as source of truth.

## Responsive layout and spacing ownership
- Parent containers own layout and spacing decisions.
- Use `gap` on parents for sibling spacing; avoid child margins for layout spacing.
- Avoid spacing duplication and alignment drift by keeping one source of truth in the parent container.
- Prefer container-level flex + `gap` patterns over per-child spacing overrides.

## Icon and label alignment rules
- For rows with variable icon sizes (for example tab bars), reserve a consistent icon slot with matching `height` and `minHeight`.
- Keep one parent-controlled vertical `gap` between icon slot and label.
- Keep labels in the main layout flow; do not place labels inside floating overlays.
- For floating/raised center icons, float only the icon container and keep label alignment in the standard row.
- Use consistent label `lineHeight` across platforms to avoid baseline drift.
